# {{.Module}}

Scaffolded with [ix](https://github.com/appsome/ix).

## Develop

```sh
cp .env.example .env
ix generate            # sqlc + gqlgen codegen from your schema
ix migrate new <name>  # diff schema.sql into a versioned Atlas migration
ix add <block>         # vendor a building block (authz, auth-jwt, helm, …)
```

The desired database schema lives in `internal/datastore/schema.sql` — edit it,
then regenerate. See `ix list` for available blocks and `ix.yaml` for project
configuration.
{{- if .PostGIS }}

### PostGIS extension

The schema uses PostGIS `geometry` types, but **`schema.sql` does not declare
the extension** and no migration creates it. This is deliberate: Atlas's
open-source CLI cannot diff PostgreSQL extensions (extension support is an
[Atlas Pro feature](https://atlasgo.io/features)), so a `CREATE EXTENSION`
statement in `schema.sql` would make `ix migrate new` fail with
`requires 'atlas login'`. PostGIS must therefore be installed **out of band**:

- **Local dev** — handled for you. `atlas.hcl` points the migration dev
  database at the multi-arch `imresamu/postgis` image (the official
  `postgis/postgis` image has no arm64 build), so `geometry` types resolve
  during diffing without managing the extension.
- **Staging / production** — install PostGIS once, before applying migrations,
  as a privileged bootstrap step:

  ```sql
  CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS postgis;
  ```

  Run this via your provisioning/IaC tooling or a DBA. Managed Postgres
  (RDS, Cloud SQL, Supabase, …) ships the PostGIS binaries; you still issue the
  `CREATE EXTENSION` once per database. Migrations assume it is already present.
{{- end }}
